Mystala/Vyxinn <p><img src=http://www.members.aol.com/rdnckgirl1/private/banner.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulililiel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lililiel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/4/01 10:31:35 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I have to say it.</span><hr size=1> I object to the imposition of new rules expected to be binding retroactively.<br>
<br>
The last time a new rule was added - the pearl requirement - it was made binding only on new additions to the list, not on those already listed. This was the right thing to do.<br>
<br>
Now another new rule has been added - no trading places - and it *is* intended to be retroactively binding on all those already on the list.<br>
<br>
Well, that's not the list I signed up for. Every person who has signed up for the list knew the rules when they signed up, and it is neither fair nor reasonable to expect those people to follow any new rule that might be added by fiat of the listkeeper.<br>
<br>
Do I have a personal interest in this? Yes. I've been talking with a friend about trading places because of personal RL circumstances that have temporarily put a severe limitation on that person's ability to play. When I signed up for the list I did so with the clear understanding that trading up would be allowable because the rules clearly said so. I don't accept the right of a listkeeper to arbitrarily add new rules and say that I must follow them. That's not right.<br>
<br>
If you want to prohibit trading places, follow precedent: do it for newcomers to the list. Don't screw those of us who were told it would be alright. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ucayleustarshine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cayleu Starshine</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/4/01 11:47:48 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Ragefire Rotation List</span><hr size=1> As always, I dont think we should try to set arbitrary rules that make no sence and ignore the wishes of the majority. Having said that, the reasons for the new requirements against trading places are simple. <br>
<br>
First, we wanted to avoid having one set of rules for some people on the list(those with pearl), and one set for another set of people on the list(those without). Making a new entrance requirement and grandfathering all existing people on the list is one thing, but once you have made it onto the list, the rules for these people ought to be uniform. Either all should trade places, or none. Obviously having those without the pearl able to trade down to escape having to leave the list is unnacceptable.<br>
<br>
Not wanting a double-standard isnt that big of a deal though, and not a good enough reason all by itself for the new rule. A much bigger concern is the new situation with people &quot;selling&quot; their place on the list. We basically could (and started to have) see a situation where a cleric gets 50, and a pearl to get on the list, but no real intention of finishing. Instead, that cleric could sell their spot in a trade for tens of thousands of plat every 4-6 weeks or so, and someone out there would pay their price. Why would it be fair for someone with rediculously deep pockets to leapfrog poorer clerics by a few weeks of waiting time?<br>
<br>
The basic reason to ever have a grandfather clause in any situation, is when a changed rule would unfairly impose an extremely harsh punishment on someone playing by the old rules. On the one hand, youve got tons of people being booted off the list entirely without this protection. On the other youve got... no trading places any more? If a changed rule will cause an extreme amount of unfair harm to someone, you may need a grandfather clause. If a changed rule is going to cause inconvenience or mild annoyance... well, that's life. People buying and selling places on the list is something we can definitely live without.<br>
<br>
I could easily be wrong though, and we could go back to the way it was if the server wants to. This would be shown with a huge outcry for doing away with the no-swap rule. However, at the moment, I do not see a majority, or even very many people at all saying the new rule is unfair. <p>Cayleu Starshine
<br><font color = blue>Healer of Tunare</font>
